    <segment id="1" parent="9" relname="span">
Usability has to do with making technology easy to learn and easy to use.</segment>
    <segment id="2" parent="12" relname="span">  I think the 
term is used to describe the quality of a user&apos;s experience when interacting with a 
computer,</segment>
    <segment id="10" parent="2" relname="elaboration"> whether its software, a cell phone, a website, or any other human operated 
device.</segment>
    <segment id="3" parent="13" relname="span"> A usable system is one which enables users to perform their job effectively and 
efficiently (Pure Interface, 2005).</segment>
    <segment id="4" parent="3" relname="elaboration">  One way that this can be accomplished is through user-
centered design.</segment>
    <segment id="5" parent="11" relname="preparation">  In terms of something having ease of use,</segment>
    <segment id="11" parent="14" relname="span"> I think it has a lot to do with 
the users ability to effectively interact with technology, software, or other systems in a 
way that doesnt require a great deal of difficulty.</segment>
    <segment id="6" parent="15" relname="span">  IBM has a website that is dedicated to 
nothing but the concept of ease of use, which I found very informative.</segment>
    <segment id="7" parent="6" relname="elaboration">  IBM believes 
that ease of use is vital to the success of most products and services.</segment>
    <segment id="8" parent="6" relname="elaboration">  They further point 
out that the user experience directly affects sales, service cost, productive use, customer 
loyalty and almost every other aspect of doing business.</segment>
